Date: Thu, 6 Feb 2003 08:54:19 -0000
From: Pablo Nart <p.nart@virgin.net

Source: enlaweb, Thu 6 Feb 2003 (translated by MJ) [edited]
<http://salud.enlaweb.com/ELW_ET_VIEWreg.asp?sch_Date=20030205135828>


Suspected vCJD case in Spain remains unconfirmed
------------------------------------------------
Juan Jose Badiola, professor of animal health and director of the National
Reference Center for Transmissible Spongiform Encephalopathies (TSE) stated
today in Zaragoza that confirmation of vCJD in a Spanish patient will not
be possible until he dies. Badiola took part in a workshop on TSE
surveillance and control, organized by the government of Aragon, and held
at the Faculty of Veterinary Medicine of the University of Zaragoza.

Professor Badiola stated that the case has been known about for some months
and that it is necessary to wait for its confirmation. Nonetheless, he
added, Spain must be prepared for the emergence of cases given that there
has been "risk." Regarding bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE) in Spain,
Badiola noted that [the peak number] of cases in the country might be
detected in 2004 and 2005 and, therefore, it could be present until 2010.

He acknowledged that veterinarians, to whom the workshop was directed, know
the disease and are aware of it, and also urged the public administrations
to take the right attitude and apply the recommended programs. Badiola
noted that the incidence of BSE in Spain is above the European mean, which
indicates that more meat meal has been consumed than was initially thought,
but that the current situation is well under control.

--
